description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/include/lichen/routing/router.h
Lines: 116-123

router.h defines:
    struct lichen_dtn_message {
        uint8_t destination_iid[8];
        uint8_t *data;              // <-- pointer
        size_t len;
        uint32_t expiry_unix;
        uint32_t buffered_at_ms;
        bool valid;
    };

But dtn.h lines 54-67 defines:
    struct lichen_dtn_message {
        uint8_t packet[CONFIG_LICHEN_DTN_MAX_PACKET_SIZE];  // <-- inline buffer
        uint16_t packet_len;
        uint8_t destination_iid[8];
        uint32_t expiry_unix;
        uint32_t buffered_at_ms;
        bool valid;
    };

These are completely different layouts! The router.h version uses a pointer, dtn.h uses an inline buffer. If code includes both headers, or uses the wrong type, memory corruption will occur.

One definition should be removed, or they should be given different names if they serve different purposes.
